explanation:

disks usage are below 80%.
action:

unneeded files on the disk.

name: %HA-HA_WD-6-DISK_USAGE
explanation:
This message is emitted when disk usage for the indicated device crosses the 80%, 95%
and 99% thresholds in either direction.
action: The indicated disk device is running out of space. Investigate disk usage.

explanation:
The sysmgr process with the indicated name and pid has been killed in an attempt to
recover system memory. The process can be manually restarted if desired, but may continue to
consume large amounts of memory.
action:
The system is critically short of memory. Automatic recovery will attempt to
stabilize the system, but there is either a memory leak or a misconfiguration. Both require operator
intervention.

name: %PORT-5-IF_DOWN_PEER_CLOSE:

explanation: The FCIP peer connected to this interface closed the TCP connection.
action:

to provide the peer IP address of this FCIP interface. Check to see why the peer closed the TCP
connection.
Introduced Cisco MDS SAN-OS Release 1.2(2a).

name: %PORT-5-IF_DOWN_PORT_BIND_FAILURE:
description: Interface [chars] is down(Isolation due to port bind failure).
explanation: Port binding failed on this port.
action:

connect to this port.
Introduced Cisco MDS SAN-OS Release 1.3(1).

name: %PORT-5-IF_DOWN_PEER_RESET:
description: Interface [chars] is down(TCP conn. reset by peer).

Fabric Manager/Device Manager procedure to provide the IP address of the peer and the route used
to connect to this FCIP peer. Check to see why the peer reset the TCP connect

name: %PORT-5-IF_DOWN_PORT_BLOCKED:
description: Interface [chars] is down(Port blocked due to FICON).
explanation: The port has been blocked by the FICON configuration.
action:
Unblock the port in the FICON configuration.
Introduced Cisco MDS SAN-OS Release 1.3(1).

name: %PORT-5-IF_DOWN_PORT_CHANNEL_MEMBERS_DOWN:
explanation: This is a PortChannel interface and all its members are operationally down.
action:

Introduced Cisco MDS SAN-OS Release 1.2(2a).

name: %PORT-5-IF_DOWN_PORT_VSAN_MISMATCH_ISOLATION:
description: Interface [chars] is down (Isolation due to port VSAN mismatch).
explanation:
The interface is isolated because of a mismatch in the configured port VSAN of the local
and remote ends.
action:
Configure the port VSAN of the local and remote interfaces to be the same and
enter the shutdown and no shutdown CLI commands or use a similar Fabric Manager/Device
Manager procedure to bring up the ports.
Introduced Cisco MDS SAN-OS Release 1

name: %PORT-5-IF_DOWN_SRC_MOD_NOT_ONLINE:
description: Interface [chars] is down(Tunnel source module not online).
explanation: The module that has the source port of this FCIP interface is not online.
action:
The module that has the source port for the FCIP link is coming online. Enter
the show module CLI command or use a similar Fabric Manager/Device Manager procedure to find
the module status.
Introduced Cisco MDS SAN-OS Release 1.2(2a).

name: %PORT-5-IF_DOWN_SUSPENDED_BY_MODE:
description: Interface [chars] is down (Suspended due to incompatible mode).
explanation:
This interface belongs to a PortChannel and the operational mode of the interface is
different from that of the PortChannel.
action:
Change the mode and the trunking mode of the PortChannel from auto and
check to ensure that the remote end of the interface also belongs to the same PortChannel.
Introduced Cisco MDS SAN-OS Release 1.2(2a).

name: %PORT-5-IF_DOWN_SUSPENDED_BY_SPEED:
description: Interface [chars] is down (Suspended due to incompatible speed).
explanation:
This interface belongs to a PortChannel and the operational speed of the interface is
different from that of the PortChannel.
action:
Change the speed of the PortChannel from auto and check to ensure that the
remote end of the interface also belongs to the same PortChannel.
Introduced Cisco MDS SAN-OS Release 1.2(2a).

address of the peer and the route used to connect to this FCIP peer. Enter the trac

provide the IP address of the peer and the route used to connect to this FCIP peer.

name: %PORT-5-IF_DOWN_SUSPENDED_BY_WWN:

is different from that of the PortChannel.
action:
Ensure that this interface is connected to the same remote switch as all the
other interfaces in the PortChannel.
Introduced Cisco MDS SAN-OS Release 1.2(2a).

name: %PORT-5-IF_DOWN_TCP_PERSIST_TIMER_EXPIRED:

action:
Check the device attached to the port and replace it if needed.
Introduced Cisco MDS SAN-OS Release 2.0(1b).

name: %PORT-5-IF_DOWN_TOO_MANY_INVALID_FLOGIS:

CLI commands or use a similar Fabric Manager/Device Manager procedure on the port.
Introduced Cisco MDS SAN-OS Release 1.3(1).

Manager procedure to determine why this VSAN is down on this interface.

action:

name: %PPP-3-AUXFAST:
description: Fast-switching to aux port, packet dropped
explanation:
A packet was fast-switched to the auxiliary port. The auxiliary port should not be part
of a dialer rotary-group, dialer pool, or multilink bundle that might be the destination of a
fast-switched packet. The packet has been dropped.
action:
Use the no ip route-cache command to disable fast switching on whatever
configuration source provides the configuration for the link to this port.

name: %PPP-4-CONFNAK:
explanation: The remote and local PPP cannot agree on a set of options that both can perform.
action: If this message recurs, copy the error message exactly as it appears and report it to your technical support representative.

name: %PPP-4-NOCLEAR:
explanation:
A multilink PPP bundle was not cleared. This error probably occurred because of a lack
of memory resources.
action:
Record the output of the show memory summary command, and then analyze
the output to find a possible memory leak.

name: %PPP-4-NOMAC:
description: no free Lex interface found with MAC address [enet]
explanation:
A LAN Extender interface could not be found with the specified MAC address when a
LAN Extender link was being brought up. This is a configuration error.
action: Refer to the documentation on configuring a LAN Extender interface.

name: %PPP-4-NOAPPOINT:
explanation:
The multilink PPP bundle was not created for the session. This error probably occurred
because of a lack of memory resources.
action:

the output to find possible memory leaks.

name: %PQUICC_ASYNC_NOMEM-3-NOMEMORY:
explanation: The router does not have enough memory to perform the requested function.
action:
Consider adding more shared memory. Copy the error message exactly as it
appears on the console or in the system log, contact your Cisco technical support representative, and
provide the representative with the gathered information.

name: %PQUICC_ETHER-5-COLL:
description: Unit [dec], excessive collisions. Retry limit [dec] exceeded
explanation: An Ethernet cable is broken or is not terminated.
action: Check cables for proper connections and termination.

name: %PQUICC_ETHER-5-LATECOLL:
explanation:
A new network may not have been engineered properly or adding a regenerator to an
existing network may have changed the network specifications. This message refers only to the
Ethernet connection and network. Ethernet has specific limitations for
action:
Ensure that your Ethernet cable is the correct length and that you do not have
too many repeaters in use. If these conditions are not the problem, try removing hosts from the
Ethernet segment to reduce the load.

name: %PQUICC_SERIAL-1-INITFAIL:
explanation:
The serial interface controller of the MPC860 quad integrated communications
controller chip could not be initialized or started for operation. This error usually indicates a
hardware problem.
action:
Power-cycle the system. If the error recurs, replace the serial interface
controller.

name: %PQUICC_FE-5-LOSTCARR:
explanation: The cable or transceiver is not connected.
action: Connect the cable or transceiver.

name: %PQUICC_SERIAL-5-LINEFLAP:
explanation:
The system has received too many modem control signal interrupts. Modem control
signals are hardware handshake signals between DTE and DCE. The signals include either a DCD
or a DSR, or both a DCD and a DSR.
action:
Check the serial interface cable. This error can occur if the cable is
disconnected or has come loose and is picking up noise. If the cable appears to be correctly
connected, check the equipment that is connected to the cable.

name: %PQUICC_SERIAL-3-CTSLOST:
explanation:
The CTS input signal on a DTE serial interface became inactive while transmitting a
frame. This problem is caused by either a communication line failure or a cable disconnection.
action:
Check the serial interface cable and the communication equipment such as the
CSU/DSU.

name: %PQUICC-5-LATECOLL:
explanation:
The Ethernet cable might be too long, or there could be too many repeaters with the
result that the delay from one end to the other is too long. The Ethernet cable might be overloaded
with too many users.
action:
Ensure that your Ethernet cable is the correct length and that you do not have
too many repeaters in use. If these conditions are not the problem, try removing hosts from the
Ethernet segment to reduce the load.

name: %PQUICC_SERIAL-5-LOSTCARR:
description: Unit [dec], carrier detect signal lost during message reception
explanation:
The DCD signal was deasserted during message reception. The DCE equipment is
responsible for asserting this signal.
action:
Check the serial interface cable. This error can occur if the cable is
disconnected.

name: %PRIVATEVLAN-3-ACL_RESTOREFAIL:

explanation: This message indicates that the system failed to apply the configuration to the ACLs.
action: Contact your technical support representative.

name: %PQUICC-5-COLL:
description: Unit [dec], excessive collisions. Retry limit [dec] exceeded
explanation: An Ethernet cable is broken or is not terminated.
action: Check cables for proper connections and termination.

name: %PRIVATEVLAN-3-ACL_MAPFAIL:
description: Unable to map ACL to VLAN
explanation: This message indicates that the system was unable to map the ACL to the VLAN.
action: Contact your technical support representative.

name: %PRIVATEVLAN-3-ACL_UNMAPFAIL:

explanation: This message indicates that the system failed to unmap the ACL from the VLAN.
action: Contact your technical support representative.

name: %QM-4-ACTION_NOT_SUPPORTED:
description: Action is not supported in policy map [chars].
explanation:
This message means that an action other than the set, trust, and police policy-map class
configuration commands was configured in a policy map. This is a hardware limitation. [chars] is
the name of the policy map.
action:
Configure only the supported actions of set, trust, and police when in
policy-map class configuration mode.

name: %QM-4-CLASS_NOT_SUPPORTED:
description: Classification is not supported in class map [chars].
explanation:
This message means that an unsupported match class-map configuration command was
configured in a policy map and attached to an egress interface or that more than one match
command was configured. This is a hardware limitation. [chars] is the class
action:
Reconfigure the class map or the policy map. Use only the match ip dscp
dscp-list class-map configuration command in a policy map that is attached to an egress interface.
Only one match per class map is supported.

name: %QM-4-AGG_POL_EXCEEDED:
explanation:
Only a limited number of aggregate policers can be supported.
On EARL7-based switches, this limit is 1023.
action: Attempt to aggregate policers if possible.

name: %QM-4-AGGREG_PLC_IGNORED:
description: police command ignored in presence of police aggregate [chars]
explanation:
If both police and police aggregate commands are specified as policy actions for the
same class, the police command is ignored as long as the aggregate has been defined by using the
mls qos aggregate command.
action: Do not specify both police and police aggregate commands in the same class.

name: %QM-4-HARDWARE_NOT_SUPPORTED:
description: Hardware limitation has been reached for policy map [chars].
explanation:
This message means that the policy-map configuration has exceeded the limitation of
the hardware. You either configured more QoS ACL entries than the number specified in the Switch
Database Management (sdm) template, or you configured more policer
action:
Reconfigure the class map or the policy map, and reduce the number of QoS
ACLs.

name: %QM-4-IDB_MODE_CHANGE_SERV_POLICY:
description: Interface [chars] service-policy is not preserved on transition to/from switchport
explanation:
The service policy applied to the interface before the transition includes features that
cannot be applied to the interface after the transition. Since a service policy is applied automatically,
none of the features in its policy map are applied a
action:
After the transition, install a different service policy on the interface, which
only includes applicable features.

name: %QM-4-POLICER_NOT_SUPPORTED:
description: Number of policers has exceeded hardware limitation for policy map [chars].
explanation:
This message means that the policy-map configuration has exceeded the limitation of
the hardware. You configured more policers in a policy map (by using the police or police aggregate
policy-map class configuration command) than supported. [chars]
action:
Reconfigure the class map or the policy map, and reduce the number of
policers.

name: %QM-4-NOT_SUPPORTED:
description: Action [chars] is not supported for a policy map attached to output side.
explanation:
This message means that a set or trust policy-map class configuration command was
configured in a policy map and attached to an egress interface. A warning message is logged, and
the actions do not take affect. This is a hardware limitation. [char
action:
Do not configure a set or trust policy-map class configuration command in a
policy map and attach it to an egress interface. These policy-map actions are supported only on
ingress interfaces.

name: %QM-4-POLICING_RATE_NOT_SUPPORTED:
description: Policer configuration has exceeded hardware limitation for policy map [chars].
explanation:
This message means that the policy-map configuration has exceeded the limitation of
the hardware. You configured a larger policing rate or burst size in a policy map (by using the police
or police aggregate policy-map class configuration command)
action:
Reconfigure the class map or the policy map, and reduce the policing rate or
burst size.

name: %QM-4-SW_SWITCH:
description: Interface [chars] routed traffic will be software switched in [chars] direction(s)
explanation:
A TCAM resource contention prevents the QoS feature from being applied in the
TCAM for this interface. The traffic on this interface will be sent to the software so that the QoS can
be applied. The configured ACLs are too large to all fit in the h
action:
Try to reduce the number of QoS rules on the interfaces to reduce TCAM
resource contention.

name: %QM-4-TCAM_CAPMAP:
description: Interface [chars] hardware TCAM LOU usage capability exceeded
explanation:
The hardware TCAM does not have the capacity to handle the number of logical
operations used with the configured ACLs on this specific interface. The hardware TCAM can
handle only up to nine logical operations per interface and up to 64
logica
action: Reduce the use of logical operations in the ACLs.

name: %QM-4-TCAM_LABEL:
explanation:
The hardware TCAM does not have the capacity to handle the number of interfaces
configured with ACLs. The hardware TCAM can handle only 500 interfaces configured with ACLs.
action: Remove ACLs from some of the interfaces.

name: %QM-4-TCAM_ENTRY:
explanation:
The hardware TCAM does not have the capacity to handle all the configured ACLs. The
configured ACLs are too large to all fit in the hardware TCAM.
action:
Share the same ACLs across multiple interfaces to reduce TCAM resource
contention.

name: %QM-4-TCAM_LOU:
explanation:
The hardware TCAM does not have the capacity to handle the number of logical
operations used with the configured ACLs. The hardware TCAM can handle only up to 9 logical
operations per interface and up to 64 logical operations in total.
action: Reduce the use of logical operations in the ACLs.

name: %QM-4-UNEXPECTED_INTERNAL_QOS_CONDITION:

debug may be enabled to obtain more information in case the condition recurs.

description: Exceeds the maximum logical operation, [chars] traffic of interface [chars] will be forwared by software
explanation:

possibility that the hardware TCAM does not have the capacity to process the number of logical
operations used with the configured rate-limit rule based on the ACLs,
action:

name: %QOS-4-INVALIDBW:
description: Not enough bandwidth to configure service-policy
explanation:
The interface bandwidth specified is less than the total bandwidth that is required for
the QoS policy on this interface.
action:
Reconfigure the service policy for the new issued bandwidth on the interface
or increase the issued interface bandwidth to the required value.

name: %QOSMGR-4-ACTION_NOT_SUPPORTED:
description: Action is not supported in policymap [chars]
explanation:
An action other than the set, trust, and police policy-map class configuration commands
was configured in a policy map. This is a hardware limitation.
action:
Configure only the supported actions of set, trust, and police when in
policy-map class configuration mode.

name: %QOS-5-POLICER_TRSTMISMATCH:
description: Mismatch in Trust specified for aggregate policer [chars]. Mismatching Trust = [chars]
explanation:
This message indicates that the aggregate policer is being used by two different ACEs
and ACLs that have different ACL trust values. The first [chars] is the policer, and the second [chars]
is the mismatching trust value.
action:
Either set the trust values the same or do not use the aggregate policer with both
ACLs and ACEs.

name: %QOSMGR-4-CLASS_NOT_SUPPORTED:
description: Classification is not supported in classmap [chars]
explanation:
This message means the an unsupported match class-map configuration command was
configured in a policy map and attached to an egress interface, or that more than one match
command was configured. This is a hardware limitation.
action:
Reconfigure the class map or the policy map. Use only the match ip dscp
dscp-list class-map configuration command in a policy map that is attached to an egress interface.
Only one match per class map is supported.

name: %QOSMGR-4-COMMAND_FAILURE:
explanation:
The command to configure a QoS setting failed. This is possible due to lack of hardware
resources. Check if any other messages along with this message indicate resource failure.
action:
If other messages indicate that the hardware resources exceeded please retry
the command with a smaller configuration. Else call your Cisco support representative and provide
the representative with gathered information.

name: %QOSMGR-4-HARDWARE_NOT_SUPPORTED:
description: Hardware limitation has reached for policymap [chars]
explanation:
The policy map configuration has exceeded the limitation of the hardware. You
configured more QoS ACL entries than the number specified in the Switch Database Management
(sdm) template.
action:
Reconfigure the class map or the policy map, and reduce the number of QoS
ACLs.

name: %QOSMGR-4-POLICER_PLATFORM_NOT_SUPPORTED:
description: Policer configuration has exceeded hardware limitation for policymap [chars]
explanation:
The policy map configuration has exceeded the limitation of the hardware. You
configured more policers together in all policy maps (by using the police or police aggregate
policy-map class configuration command) than supported by hardware.
action:
Reconfigure the class map or the policy map or delete policy from
someinterfaces.

name: %QUICC_ETHER-5-COLL:
description: Unit [dec], excessive collisions. Retry limit [dec] exceeded
explanation: An Ethernet cable is broken or is not terminated.
action: Check the cables for proper connections and termination.

name: %QUICC_ETHER-5-HBEAT:
explanation:
The Ethernet cable might be too long, or there could be too many repeaters, causing the
delay from one end to the other to be too long. The Ethernet cable might be overloaded with too
many users.
action:
Ensure that your Ethernet cable is the correct length and that you do not have
too many repeaters in use. If these conditions are not the problem, try removing hosts from the
Ethernet segment to reduce the load.

name: %QUICC_ETHER-5-LATECOLL:
explanation:

delay from one end to the other to be too long. The Ethernet cable might be overloaded with too

too many repeaters in use. If these conditions are not the problem, try removing hosts from the
Ethernet segment to reduce the load.

CSU/DSU.

production Cisco
IOS image is running. If not, replace the unit.

action: Contact your Cisco technical support representative to replace the unit.

name: %QUICC_SERIAL-5-LINEFLAP:
explanation:
The system has received too many modem control signal interrupts. Modem control
signals are hardware handshake signals between DTE and DCE. The signals include either a DCD
or a DSR, or both a DCD and a DSR.
action:
Check the serial interface cable. The error can occur if the cable is
disconnected or has come loose and is picking up noise. If the cable appears to be correctly
connected, check the equipment connected to the cable.

name: %RADIO-4-DSPHPITIMEOUT:

action:

gathered information.

description: Radio[dec]/0, Error processing indication from DSP "[chars]" ([chars]:[dec])
explanation:

action:

gathered information.

name: %RADIO-4-DSPSPURRESP:

action:

name: %RADIO-4-DSPULOFLOW:
description: Radio[dec]/0, uplink message queue overflow reported by DSP "[chars]"
explanation:
At least one DSP-to-router message was lost because the uplink queue of that DSP was
full. DSP-to-router messages can be lost when many thresholds, histograms, or timelines are being
triggered or are expiring at the same time.
action:
Change the thresholds or reduce histogram or time line usage to ease the load
on the system.

action:
